LiteDB migration notes

This file documents the migration from the legacy JSON persistence (data.json) to an embedded LiteDB single-file database used by BookCollection.

Overview
- The project now uses LiteDB (embedded NoSQL) to store books in a single file named `books.db` by default.
- On construction, BookCollection will attempt to migrate an existing `data.json` into the LiteDB file if the DB is empty.
- After a successful migration the original `data.json` is renamed to `data.json.migrated` to avoid duplicate migrations.

Behavior and locations
- Default DB file: `books.db` in the application base directory (the same location `data.json` previously lived).
- You can pass a custom path to the BookCollection constructor. If the path ends with `.db` it will be used as the DB file; if it ends with `.json` it will be treated as the legacy JSON path and migrated into a same-named `.db` file.

Schema and indexes
- Books are stored as documents in the `books` collection. The existing `Book` model shape (Title, Author, Year, Read) is preserved — no explicit Id property was added.
- Indexes: Title and Author indexes are created automatically for fast lookups.

Migration notes
- If `data.json` is invalid JSON, migration is skipped and a console warning is emitted; the existing DB (if any) is left unchanged.
- If migration encounters an I/O error the operation reports a warning and continues; no data is lost by this operation.

Testing notes
- Unit tests now use a per-test temporary `.db` file and ensure BookCollection is disposed to avoid file locks.
- When writing new tests that interact with the DB, always dispose the BookCollection instance before deleting or replacing the DB file.

Operational notes
- LiteDB locks the DB file while it is open. For the console app this is acceptable (the OS will release handles on process exit); if you run multiple processes against the same DB use the `Connection=shared` option (already configured in the project) or run a single shared instance.

Rollback & backups
- The migration renames `data.json` to `data.json.migrated` — keep the migrated file as a backup until you verify the DB contents.

References
- LiteDB official: https://www.litedb.org/
